# Coding standards

## Modern ESM JavaScript

- Use `const` with arrow functions instead of function declarations when it fits the codebase’s existing style.
- Wrap arrow function parameters in parentheses consistently with project convention.
- Prefer explicit braces and explicit `return` unless the file already standardizes on expression-bodied arrows for trivial callbacks.
- Consolidate consecutive one-line comments into one concise comment or a proper multiline comment.
- Avoid dashes in prose comments unless a technical term requires one.
- Add JSDoc where the project already documents exports, public APIs, or non-obvious behavior.

## CSS and design tokens

- Before adding new colors, spacing, typography scales, or motion values, look for an **existing design system or token layer** (variables, theme files, Tailwind config, CSS custom properties in a `tokens` or `theme` path, etc.). Paths differ per repo; discover them instead of assuming a layout.
- Add or extend shared tokens only when no suitable token exists and the value is reused or should be systemic. One-off layout tweaks can stay local to the component rule.
- Prefer consuming tokens (`var(--...)`, theme classes, etc.) over duplicating the same raw values in many files.

## CSS class names and structure

- Avoid BEM-style noise unless the project already commits to BEM; skip `block__element` / `block--modifier` if the codebase does not use it.
- Prefer semantic markup and a small number of purposeful hooks over long utility chains on every node when the same result is clear with a root class and descendants.
- Name things for what they are in context; avoid misleading or purely structural labels when meaning exists in the domain.
- Skip new classes that only duplicate what the element or role already expresses.

## CSS authoring style

- **Nesting:** If the project uses native CSS nesting (or a preprocessor with nested rules), mirror the DOM: rules for a child that structurally belongs under a parent should live nested under that parent’s block when practical, with `&:hover`, `&:focus-visible`, etc. where the compiled selector must continue from the parent.
- **Scope:** Follow the prevailing pattern in the repo (CSS modules, scoped SFC styles, plain global layers). Do not introduce a second parallel system without a reason.
- **Cascade glue:** `@import`, `@layer`, and similar ordering may stay at file top or in flat sections when required for cascade or tooling; avoid burying them where order breaks.
- **Features:** Prefer what the repo’s browserslist and build pipeline support; avoid legacy patterns only when they are still mandated by the project.

## HTML headings

When you author visible `<h1>`–`<h6>` text in markup, use **Chicago headline-style title case** and do not depend on `text-transform` alone; see **Chicago title case headings** (`.cursor/rules/chicago-title-case-headings.mdc`). Narrow or widen that rule’s `globs` to match where your headings live.

## Project-specific rhythms

Courseware, docs sites, or app-specific UX rules (for example “unit index pages assume X flows into Y”) do **not** belong in this portable rule. Add a **separate** rule file in `.cursor/rules/` for that repository if you need those constraints.
